docs.abstract: Prosecutors recommended charging a New York police officer, but others question whether the case can be won. Mr. Garner’s gasps of “I can’t breathe” galvanized protesters.
docs.snippet: Prosecutors recommended charging a New York police officer, but others question whether the case can be won. Mr. Garner’s gasps of “I can’t breathe” galvanized protesters.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Federal civil rights prosecutors have recommended charges against a New York police officer in the 2014 death of Eric Garner, three current and former officials said, but top Justice Department officials have expressed strong reservations about whether to move forward with a case they say may not be winnable.

headline.main: Charges Sought in Eric Garner’s Death, but Justice Officials Have Doubts
headline.print_headline: Justice Dept. Is Seen as Divided On Rights Case in Garner Killing

docs.abstract: After the Senate voted to confirm Mike Pompeo to be the nation’s 70th secretary of state, he turned to urgent problems around the world.
docs.snippet: After the Senate voted to confirm Mike Pompeo to be the nation’s 70th secretary of state, he turned to urgent problems around the world.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Senate easily confirmed Mike Pompeo on Thursday as the United States’ 70th secretary of state, elevating the current C.I.A. director and an outspoken foreign policy hawk to be the nation’s top diplomat.

headline.main: Senate Confirms C.I.A. Chief Mike Pompeo to Be Secretary of State
headline.print_headline: Unreserved Hawk Is Confirmed as Top Diplomat, With Votes to Spare

docs.abstract: The president and the rapper share a history of unpredictable behavior — and a delight in dividing the public.
docs.snippet: The president and the rapper share a history of unpredictable behavior — and a delight in dividing the public.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — As crazy as it seems — though in this world, that’s a high bar — the mercurial president accused of racist comments and the bombastic rapper accused of supporting him have long seemed to enjoy each other’s company.

headline.main: Trump and Kanye West Share Praise-Filled Tweets. And, Apparently, ‘Dragon Energy.’

docs.abstract: On Friday, the White House said a thorough review of vehicle incident reports conducted by administration officials revealed no crashes that matched an accusation against Dr. Ronny L. Jackson.
docs.snippet: On Friday, the White House said a thorough review of vehicle incident reports conducted by administration officials revealed no crashes that matched an accusation against Dr. Ronny L. Jackson.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The White House challenged reports that Dr. Ronny L. Jackson, the president’s doctor, had been involved in a drunken driving crash, citing on Friday what it said was a thorough review of vehicle incident reports conducted by administration officials.

headline.main: White House Says Records Don’t Match Accusation Against Jackson
headline.print_headline: White House Says Records Dispute Senator’s Allegation

docs.abstract: The questions provide the most detailed look yet at the special counsel investigation and show an effort to learn about the president’s thinking.
docs.snippet: The questions provide the most detailed look yet at the special counsel investigation and show an effort to learn about the president’s thinking.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Robert S. Mueller III, the special counsel investigating Russia’s election interference, has at least four dozen questions on an exhaustive array of subjects he wants to ask President Trump to learn more about his ties to Russia and determine whether he obstructed the inquiry itself, according to a list of the questions obtained by The New York Times.

headline.main: Mueller Has Dozens of Inquiries for Trump in Broad Quest on Russia Ties and Obstruction
headline.print_headline: Questions for President Show Depth of Inquiry Into Russian Meddling

docs.abstract: President Trump’s longtime physician said Tuesday that he was aggressively cut out of the Trump orbit early last year and that two aides seized Mr. Trump’s medical records without authorization.
docs.snippet: President Trump’s longtime physician said Tuesday that he was aggressively cut out of the Trump orbit early last year and that two aides seized Mr. Trump’s medical records without authorization.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump’s longtime physician said in an interview published Tuesday that after he told The New York Times that Mr. Trump took a drug to promote hair growth, two Trump aides staged what he called “a raid” of his Manhattan office in February 2017 and removed all of Mr. Trump’s medical files.

headline.main: Trump’s Former Doctor Says Office Was Raided and Files Seized
headline.print_headline: Doctor Says Trump Aides Raided His Office for Files

Brennan, the former director of the Central Intelligence Agency, said Wednesday that he thought Russia may have some kind of compromising information on President Trump, setting off furious speculation about whether the former spy chief was basing that assertion on inside information.

docs.abstract: Without major change, spending bills that are too big to veto will most likely remain the standard in Congress, despite President Trump’s insistence that he’ll never sign one again.
docs.snippet: Without major change, spending bills that are too big to veto will most likely remain the standard in Congress, despite President Trump’s insistence that he’ll never sign one again.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump insisted he will never again sign a huge catchall spending measure of the sort he just grudgingly approved to fund the government. But he will probably have little choice if he wants to keep the government open in the future.

headline.main: Broad Spending Bills Here to Stay as Long as Congressional Dysfunction Reigns
headline.print_headline: Bills ‘Too Large to Veto’ Indicate Bigger Problems

docs.abstract: A programming error caused top law enforcement officials to overstate how many locked smartphones it was unable to search, including in congressional testimony.
docs.snippet: A programming error caused top law enforcement officials to overstate how many locked smartphones it was unable to search, including in congressional testimony.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The F.B.I. came under fire from electronic privacy and security advocates on Wednesday after acknowledging that it has repeatedly exaggerated the number of locked smartphones and other mobile electronic devices it has been unable to access because of encryption, including in congressional testimony and public speeches.

headline.main: F.B.I. Admits Overstating Locked Phone Problem, and Critics Pounce
headline.print_headline: Problem of Locked Devices Was Overstated

docs.abstract: The Iowa congressman, who retweeted a Nazi sympathizer, seems to be protected by his eight-term incumbency and the fact that people are so used to his racist remarks that they just shrug their shoulders.
docs.snippet: The Iowa congressman, who retweeted a Nazi sympathizer, seems to be protected by his eight-term incumbency and the fact that people are so used to his racist remarks that they just shrug their shoulders.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When Arthur Jones, a Holocaust denier, ran as a Republican in an Illinois congressional primary, the state Republican Party denounced him as a Nazi. When he won, party leaders quickly vowed to back an independent candidate.

headline.main: Steve King’s Inflammatory Behavior Is Met With Silence From G.O.P.
headline.print_headline: Racially Charged Antics Are Met With Silence in G.O.P.
